				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Zacatac wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I have also made a new LOOT key.
<br />

<br />
/pet target
<br />
/pause 1
<br />
/assist
<br />
/pause 1
<br />
/loot
<br />

<br />
When a mob dies, pet still has the corpse of mob on its target until you tell it to attack something else.  So it makes for fast, easy looting without having to click on corpses.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I tried that combination.  It works fine except when your pet is fighting mulitple mobs.  
<br />

<br />
I also tried 
<br />

<br />
/target a
<br />
/pause 3
<br />
/loot.  
<br />

<br />
This works for most mobs but not all mobs are named "a XXXXXXX"
<br />

<br />
My current key is
<br />
/pause 3, /pet target 
<br />
/assist
<br />
/pause 3, /target a
<br />
/loot
<br />

<br />
This key works in all cases where the corpse is closer to me than any mob and starts with an "a".  It also works when the corpse doesn't start with an '"a" and my pet is only fighting one mob.  If I am fighting in a zone where most of the mobs don't start with an a, I will add the line
<br />
/pause 3, /target "X" where "X" is the first letter of the mobs I kill most of between the /pause 3, /target 1 and /loot line. 
<br />

<br />
I very seldom have to manually click on the mobs to loot any more.<br />_________________<br />Dabrighter Blazemeister
